Chicagoans remain divided after Obama's Syria speech

Much like Congress, those in the Chicago area were split on whether the U.S.
should intervene

     * [126]print

     *
     *

   IFRAME:
   [127]http://embed.newsinc.com/Single/iframe.html?WID=2&VID=25153896&fre
   ewheel=90921&sitesection=sechicagotribune&height=400&width=600

   Rogers Park resident Oona O'Leary gives her thoughts on a possible U.S.
   military strike against Syria, at the Heartland Cafe's Buffalo
   Bar.(John J. Kim/Chicago Tribune)
   By Lauren Zumbach, Michelle Manchir and Mitch Smith Tribune reporters

   7:01 a.m. CDT, September 11, 2013

   At the Heartland Cafe, a restaurant in the Rogers Park neighborhood
   known for its left-leaning politics, about two dozen anti-war activists
   gathered Tuesday to watch President Barack Obama's prime-time speech
   urging congressional support for U.S. military intervention in Syria.

   No matter what Obama said during his nationally televised address, many
   at the cafe said they wouldn't be persuaded to support it.

   "They just don't work. We've tried a million ways with terrible results
   for everyone involved," said Katy Hogan, Heartland's owner. "I don't
   think we've even begun to try all the nonviolent ways to intervene."
