   But much like Congress, those in the Chicago area were split on whether
   the U.S. should intervene in Syria, where more than two years of civil
   war have left upward of 100,000 people dead.

   Mufaddal Hamadeh, a Syrian-American, watched the speech at his suburban
   home with family and friends. He said Obama's presentation effectively
   laid out the reasons for a limited U.S. intervention.

   "He answered a lot of critics about why do we need to go to war,"
   Hamadeh said.

   The group of Syrian-Americans at Hamadeh's home, all of whom still have
   family in the Middle East, generally support U.S. intervention that
   could weaken the government of Syrian President Bashar Assad, who is
   accused of using chemical weapons on his own people.

   Obama's speech came as a Russia-led diplomatic solution emerged for the
   humanitarian crisis. If the tenuous negotiations succeed, Syria would
   surrender its chemical arsenal to international control and avoid
   Western military intervention.

   Michael James, Chicago's 49th Ward Democratic Party president, let out
   a quiet cheer at the Heartland Cafe when Obama talked about "hopeful
   developments" for a diplomatic solution.

   Though James and several other viewers acknowledged the need for
   skepticism about the seriousness of Russia's proposal and the
   difficulty of ensuring that the Syrian government would actually
   comply, they said it was still better than a military alternative.

   Not everyone made watching Obama's speech a priority. Pedestrians
   streamed by a Loop television studio where screens facing the sidewalk
   showed Obama pressing his case. About a block away, anti-war
   demonstrators who marched through downtown earlier in the evening were
   packing up their supplies as Obama spoke.

   One demonstrator, Ryan Metz, said he wished the president would focus
   more on feeding the hungry in refugee camps than plotting airstrikes.
   Though he planned to watch a recording of the speech later, his mind
   was already made up.

   "The Middle East is a place where every time we get involved," Metz
   said, "we seem to do a lot more harm than good."

   A few blocks away, Harold Washington College student Henry Ortiz said
   he hadn't followed the Syria debate closely, but said he trusted the
   president and government to make the right call. He also didn't watch
   Obama's speech.

   For those some people following the Syria issue more closely, Obama's
   speech marked a turning point.

   Hogan, the Heartland Cafe owner, said she was pleased to see Obama
   taking the time to consider alternatives, after what initially seemed
   like a stronger push for immediate, punitive strikes.

   "Nonmilitary options may take more time, but they don't require bullets
   into people's bodies," she said. "If we are the strongest nation on
   Earth, the best way to show that is to show restraint."

   Those who gathered at Hamadeh's home said military action must follow
   or more Syrians will perish at Assad's hands.

   "We don't want one more child to die," Hamadeh said.

